## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified compliance mapping today is understanding the difference between control coverage and control traceability.

Control coverage answers: does a control exist for every requirement? A compliance mapping table that lists a control for every HIPAA provision demonstrates coverage. Coverage is necessary but not sufficient.

Control traceability answers: for any specific regulatory requirement, can an auditor follow a documented path from the requirement to the specific control implementation to the evidence that the control is working? Traceability is what makes compliance defensible in an OCR investigation — not the assertion that controls exist, but the documented chain of evidence that proves they work.

The 2013 Advocate Medical Group breach discussed in Day 75 and Day 82 illustrates the traceability gap: Advocate had encryption policies. The unencrypted laptops represented a control coverage gap — the policy existed, but the specific asset category was not covered. An auditor who traced the encryption requirement through the policy to the asset inventory would have identified that laptops were out of scope.

For the OpenMRS compliance mapping, traceability means that for every HIPAA requirement, the mapping includes not just the control but the specific implementation artifact (SSP section), the assessment evidence (SAR finding), and the current monitoring evidence (Config rule, quarterly review record, POA&M status).

