## Why Honest Compliance Mapping Matters

The two ⚠️ entries in the compliance summary — the CP-2 emergency access procedure in progress and the AU-12 denied-access logging gap — might tempt a less honest compliance mapping approach to show them as compliant: the CP-2 has compensating controls, and the AU-12 gap was self-identified and is being addressed. An optimistic compliance table could show all green.

The honest mapping shows the partial status because an OCR auditor or formal assessor who finds these gaps during an investigation — and finds that the compliance mapping represented them as compliant — is looking at a documentation credibility problem, not just a control gap. The organization that finds its own gaps and documents them honestly is in a fundamentally different position than one that discovers gaps under audit pressure.

This connects to the Touchstone Medical Imaging settlement from Day 80: inaccurate representations during an OCR investigation resulted in a significantly larger settlement than the underlying violations would have warranted. Honest documentation, even when it shows gaps, is the only sustainable compliance posture.

