## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The four-layer compliance mapping approach — from requirement through NIST control through SSP implementation through evidence chain — is validated by how OCR structures its HIPAA compliance investigations.

The **2019 University of Rochester Medical Center settlement ($3 million)** involved OCR finding that URMC had impermissibly disclosed ePHI — specifically through unencrypted personal health information on lost and stolen portable devices. The investigation found that URMC's risk analysis had identified unencrypted mobile devices as a risk, but the risk management process had not addressed the risk with appropriate controls.

The compliance mapping lesson: URMC could demonstrate that they had conducted a risk analysis (Layer 1 requirement met) and had identified the risk (Layer 2 control awareness). The failure was in Layers 3 and 4 — the implementation did not address the identified risk, and the evidence chain would have shown unencrypted devices still in use despite the risk analysis.

A compliance mapping that traces through all four layers would have made this gap visible before the breach: the encryption requirement (§164.312(a)(2)(iv)) mapped to the risk analysis finding, mapped to the implementation status, would have shown "risk identified, implementation incomplete." That gap representation in the compliance mapping is what drives the remediation that prevents the incident.

